'''Blaschko's lines''', also called the '''Lines of Blaschko''', are [[skin]] lines invisible under normal conditions. They become apparent when some diseases of the skin or [[mucosa]] manifest themselves according to these patterns. They follow a "V" shape over the back, "S" shaped whorls over the chest, stomach, and sides, and wavy shapes on the head.<ref>{{cite book|title=Transcription|author=Brown, Philip M.|page=38|year=2002|publisher=CRC Press|url=http://books.google.com/?id=MWdS56hbkbEC&pg=PA38&dq=%22blaschko%27s+lines%22 | isbn=978-0-415-27200-1}}</ref>

The lines are believed to trace the migration of [[embryonic cell]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Textbook of Pediatric Dermatology|author=Harper, John|page=691|url=http://books.google.com/?id=z0PEdterBCwC&pg=PA691&dq=%22blaschko%27s+lines%22year=2000|isbn=0-86542-939-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Neurocutaneous Disorders: Phakomatoses & Hamartoneoplastic Syndromes|author=Ruggieri, Martino|page=569|year=2008|publisher=Springer|url=http://books.google.com/?id=b1NI28tR4hIC&pg=PA569&dq | isbn=978-3-211-21396-4}}</ref> The stripes are a type of genetic [[mosaicism]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Neurocutaneous Disorders|author=Roach, Ewell S.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=98|year=2004|url=http://books.google.com/?id=-kEYmZs-csgC&pg=PA98&dq=%22blaschko%27s+lines%22 | isbn=978-0-521-78153-4}}</ref> They do not correspond to [[nervous system|nervous]], [[muscular system|muscular]], or [[lymphatic system]]s. The lines can be observed in other animals such as cats and dogs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Muller & Kirk's small animal dermatology|author=Muller, George and Kirk, Robert|year=2001|page=9|url=http://books.google.com/?id=aK2XZdCiwdwC&pg=PA9&dq=%22blaschko%27s+lines%22|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences | isbn=978-0-7216-7618-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Veterinary Dermatopathology|author=Gross, Thelma Lee|page=156|url=http://books.google.com/?id=VKa2Wo3Wc-kC&pg=PA156&dq=%22blaschko%27s+lines%22|year=2004 | isbn=978-0-632-06452-6 | publisher=Wiley-Blackwell}}</ref>

[[Germans|German]] [[dermatology|dermatologist]] [[Alfred Blaschko]] is credited for the first demonstration of these lines in 1901.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Blaschko, Alfred|year=1901|title=Die Nervenverteilung in der Haut in ihre Beziehung zu den Erkrankungen der Haut}}</ref>

== Conditions distributed along Blaschko's lines ==

[[File:Maculae Bloch-Sulzberger syndrome.jpg|[[Incontinentia pigmenti]] forming along Blaschko's lines in a 3-year-old girl.|thumb]]
The skin lesions that follow the Blaschko's lines are varied. They include [[genetics|genetic]], [[congenital]] and acquired (i.e. non-genetic) conditions.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Bolognia JL, Orlow SJ, Glick SA | year = 1994 | month = | title = Lines of Blaschko | journal = Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology | pmid = 8040398 | volume = 31 | issue = 2 | pages = 157â€“190 | doi = 10.1016/S0190-9622(94)70143-1}}</ref> Examples include:
* Pigmentary disorders
** [[Naevus achromicus]] (including hypomelanosis of Ito)
** [[Nevus|Epidermal Naevus]]
*** [[Nevus sebaceous]]
*** Inflammatory linear verrucous naevus
* [[X-linked]] [[genetics|genetic]] skin disorder
** [[Incontinentia pigmenti]]
** [[CHILD syndrome]]
*Acquired inflammatory skin rashes
** [[Lichen striatus]]
** [[lichen planus]]
** [[lupus erythematosus]]
*[[Chimerism]]

